<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-03-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-03-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="605" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d605">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 868.001 G 29/4.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-03-19">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 19, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The Queen received the President’s message of condolence just before she
                            left for Saloniki. It was the first message to arrive from any foreign
                            country and has been published conspicuously by the afternoon
                            newspapers.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>